Light morph appeared at 11:30 - close-in, dropped below cliffs and resighted about 10 minutes later by Jonah B., at his house about 1/4 mile south.    Adult appeared at 11:39am and on and off again for about 45 minutes - initially tried to cross the gate (northward) in a very heavy wind and got dangerously close to water about half way across.  Came back to the Presidio and hung around for a while, occasionally harassed by a Red-Tailed Hawk and by the crows.  Last seen gaining elevation north of Fort Scott in what seemed to be a second attempt to cross.  My guess is that it blew too far south in the 75 mph winds and was trying to reposition northward.

Soaring with RTHAs on the north of road, around windmills at about MM 5.6.   White headed hawk, white on chest, very dark belly.  Distinct black carpal patches and commas.   Tail has wide black band, otherwise whitish.

photos.Locality: Carrizo Plain NM (use specific hotspots when available)
photos.Observation Details: between Traver Ranch and Panorama rd turnoff, we were following an adult Ferruginous Hawk from a perch to flight from our vantage point on Soda Lk Rd. For a minute or so, it was joined in fairly close proximity by this immature or female Rough-legged Hawk, both circling around each other. Immediately apparent were the rather diffuse dark subterminal band on the tail, and the rather sharply defined dark carpal patches. The wings were pinched in somewhat at their base with a corresponding secondary bulge. The primary wing tips were black.

This juvenile owl was first spotted by a neighbor who found it day-roosting in a street tree on Alabama Street on July 31st.   I went to look for it the next morning, but it was not seen again for several days.  Quite surprisingly the owl returned to the exact same spot on August 5th when I was able to see and photograph it.  The bird appears to be in juvenile plumage, with fresh crisp feathers pre-molt.  It stayed immobilized about 10' off of the sidewalk in a dark spot in the tree.  Surprisingly there do not appear to be any summer records in eBird of Saw-whets, only winter sightings ranging from 11/13 to 4/09.  Hard to say whether this bird bred locally or is ranging widely post-dispersal.   Saw-whets breed on the peninsula, starting at La Honda - but maybe closer in the Crystal Springs watershed (?), as well as to the north at Mt Tam and in small numbers in the Berkeley Hills.  Do juveniles typically wander 20+ miles prior to molt and feed on their own?  And would it stay in place for at least six days?  It seems equally likely that there was an undetected successful nesting in the general area.  There are mature trees in the neighborhood, but no closed canopy forest.  Mystery worth considering, especially if this bird shows up again.

Appeared very close to the trail at 34.4634888,-119.7564543.  This is a hill with a lot of native oaks, some stressed or dead, others looking pretty healthy.  This would seem to be a suitable grove for them to set up for winter.  Bird was apparent adult, caching food in a snag.   Allowed for very close prolonged looks.  Saw a pale juvenile type bird later in a healthy oak tree about 100 yards west - subsequent visitors have confirmed that these are different birds (an adult and a juvenile.)  Photo taken by my son with a standard (non-zoom) camera lens.
